### PHP File Write

PHP provides several functions for writing data to files.

### Writing Methods

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `fwrite()` / `fputs()` | Write to an open file |
| `file_put_contents()` | Write string to file (simplest) |
| `fputcsv()` | Write a line as CSV |

### Examples

```php
<?php
// Simple write (overwrites)
file_put_contents("test.txt", "Hello, World!\n");

// Append using FILE_APPEND flag
file_put_contents("test.txt", "More data\n", FILE_APPEND);

// Using fwrite
$file = fopen("test.txt", "a"); // Append mode
fwrite($file, "Appended line\n");
fputs($file, "Another line\n"); // fputs is alias
fclose($file);
?>
```

### LOCK_EX for Safety

```php
<?php
// Prevent concurrent writes
file_put_contents("log.txt", $data, FILE_APPEND | LOCK_EX);
?>
```

### Writing CSV

```php
<?php
$file = fopen("data.csv", "w");
$headers = ["Name", "Email", "Age"];
fputcsv($file, $headers);

$rows = [
    ["John", "john@example.com", 30],
    ["Jane", "jane@example.com", 25]
];
foreach ($rows as $row) {
    fputcsv($file, $row);
}
fclose($file);
?>
```

> **Key Point:** `file_put_contents()` is the easiest way to write files. Use `FILE_APPEND` to add to existing content instead of overwriting.
